.TH VOIX 1 "March 2026" "Voix 2.3.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
voix \- privilege escalation tool replacing sudo/doas
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B voix
[\fIOPTIONS\fR]
[\fICOMMAND\fR [\fIARGS\fR...]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Voix is a modern, secure, and easy-to-use privilege escalation tool.
It provides a flexible rule-based system for granting permissions and uses PAM for authentication.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-u, \-\-user \fIUSER\fR
Execute command as the specified user (default: root).
.TP
.B \-C, \-\-clear
Clear any persisted authentications for the current user.
.TP
.B \-n, \-\-non-interactive
Fail if a password is required, rather than prompting.
.SH CONFIGURATION
The Voix configuration file, located at \fI/etc/voix.conf\fR, defines the rules for command execution.
.PP
The syntax is as follows:
.PP
.B (permit|deny) [nopass] <ident> [as <target>] [cmd <command> [args ...]]
.PP
.TP
.B permit
Allow the user to execute a command.
.TP
.B deny
Prevent the user from executing a command.
.TP
.B nopass
The user will not be prompted for a password.
.TP
.B ident
The user or group to apply the rule to. Groups must be prefixed with a colon (e.g., :wheel).
.TP
.B target
The user to execute the command as (defaults to root).
.TP
.B command
The command to be executed. If no command is specified, any command is allowed.
.TP
.B args
A list of arguments for the command.
.SH AUTHENTICATION
Voix uses the Pluggable Authentication Modules (PAM) framework for authentication.
The service name is \fBvoix\fR, and its configuration can be found in \fI/etc/pam.d/voix\fR.
.SH EXAMPLES
Execute \fBwhoami\fR as root:
.IP
voix whoami
.PP
Execute \fBwhoami\fR as a specific user:
.IP
voix -u user whoami
.PP
Start a shell as root:
.IP
voix -s
.SH FILES
.TP
.B /etc/voix.conf
Main configuration file for access rules.
.TP
.B /etc/pam.d/voix
PAM configuration for authentication.
.TP
.B /var/log/voix.log
Log file for Voix commands.
.SH SECURITY
Voix should be owned by root and have the setuid bit set for proper functionality.
.SH AUTHOR
Veridian-Zenith Team
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR sudo (8),
.BR doas (1),
.BR pam (8)
